<exercise.pack xmlns="Compositor"
               xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
               id="Exe_MatrixOperations-TrueFalse"
               xsi:schemaLocation="Compositor file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Compositor.xsd">
	  <texsupport href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>
	  <title>Matrix Operations: Exercises</title>
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Let <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                  </math>, <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                  </math>, and <math>
                     <latex>\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                  </math> be matrices of size <math>
                     <latex>(3,3)</latex>
                  </math>. Indicate whether the following statements are always true. – Justify each answer.</para.body>
            </para>
         </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}(B+C) = \Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B} + \Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>This statement is always true.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This statement is always true. – Reason: matrix multiplication distributes over matrix addition.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}\cdot \IdMtrx[4] = \Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This statement is false.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This statement is false. – Reason: the product of the <math>
                           <latex>(3,3)</latex>
                        </math>-matrix <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math> by the <math>
                           <latex>(4,4)</latex>
                        </math>-matrix <math>
                           <latex>\IdMtrx[4]</latex>
                        </math> is not defined.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}(\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{C}) = (\Mtrx{A} \Mtrx{B})\Mtrx{C}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Yes! - This statement is always true.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Recall the rules for matrix multiplication.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This statement is true. – Reason: this follows from the associative law of matrix multiplication.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2 \Mtrx{A}^3 = \Mtrx{A}^6</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This statement is not always true.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This statement is not always true. – Reason: <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2\Mtrx{A}^3 = (\Mtrx{A} \Mtrx{A}) (\Mtrx{A} \Mtrx{A} \Mtrx{A}) = \Mtrx{A}^5</latex>
                        </math>. For example when <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A} = 2\cdot \IdMtrx[3]</latex>
                        </math>, we find</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\Mtrx{A}^6 = 64\cdot \IdMtrx[3] \neq 32\cdot \IdMtrx[3] = \Mtrx{A}^5</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore this statement is not always true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A} - \Mtrx{B})(\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{B}) = \Mtrx{A}^2 - \Mtrx{B}^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This statement is not always true!</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Expand the brackets using the properties of matrix multiplication.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We expand the brackets using the distributivity law of matrix multiplication repeatedly:</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A} - \Mtrx{B})(\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{B})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}(\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{B})\ -\ \Mtrx{B}(\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{B})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2 + \Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B} - \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A} - \Mtrx{B}^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>If <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                        </math> were always equal to <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math>, we could cancel the terms in the middle and arrive at the proposed ‘identity’. We know, however, that <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                        </math> can be distinct from <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math>. So there is no reason why the proposed ‘identity’ should hold. In fact, there are choices of <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                        </math> where it is false. For example, let</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
							A := 
							\left[
							\begin{array}{rrr}
							1 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 \\
							1 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\
							0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
							\end{array}
							\right]\qquad \text{and} \qquad
							B :=
							\left[
							\begin{array}{rrr}
							2 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
							0 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
							1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1
							\end{array}
							\right]
							
						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Then</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A} - \Mtrx{B})(\Mtrx{A}+\Mtrx{B})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>
							
							\left[
							\begin{array}{rrr}
							-1 &amp; -1 &amp; -2 \\
							1 &amp; 2 &amp; -1 \\
							-1 &amp; -1 &amp; -1 
							\end{array}
							\right]\cdot
							\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
							3 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \\
							1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \\
							1 &amp; 1 &amp; 3
							\end{array}
							\right]
							
						</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>
							
							\left[
							\begin{array}{rrr}
							-4 &amp; 0 &amp; -2 \\
							0 &amp; 2 &amp; 0 \\
							-2 &amp; -2 &amp; -4
							\end{array}
							\right]
							
						</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>On the other hand</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2 - \Mtrx{B}^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>
							
							\left[
							\begin{array}{rrr}
							0 &amp; -2 &amp; -1 \\
							2 &amp; 0 &amp; -3 \\
							0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
							\end{array}\right] -
							\left[
							\begin{array}{rrr}
							5 &amp; 1 &amp; 4 \\
							0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
							4 &amp; 1 &amp; 5
							\end{array}
							\right]
							
						</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex/>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>
							
							\left[
							\begin{array}{rrr}
							-5 &amp; -3 &amp; -5 \\
							2 &amp; -1 &amp; -3 \\
							-4 &amp; -1 &amp; -4
							\end{array}
							\right]
							
						</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This example shows that the suggested matrix ‘identity’ is not always true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Whenever matrices <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math> satisfy the identity <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B} = \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math>, then   <math>
                        <latex>(\Mtrx{A}+\Mtrx{B})^2 = \Mtrx{A}^2 + 2\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B} + \Mtrx{B}^2</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>This statement is always true.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Expand the brackets using the distributivity law of matrix multiplication.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We compute, using the distributivity law of matrix multiplication</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>(\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{B})^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Mtrx{A}^2 + \Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B} + \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{B}^2</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Now the proposed identity follows from the assumption that <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                        </math> are matrices for which <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{A}\Mtrx{B} = \Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
					
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
</exercise.pack>
